<h1 class="what_is_top_up">What is TopUp?</h1>
<p>
  TopUp is an easy to use Javascript library for unobstrusively displaying images and webpages in a Web 2.0 approach of popups.
  The library is <%= link_to "JQuery", "http://jquery.com" %> driven in order to maintain cross-browser compatibility and compactness.
  TopUp offers the following advantages:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>A very easy setup process</li>
  <li>The ability of displaying images, iframes, webpages and pure HTML</li>
  <li>TopUp can be used along with Prototype (just include TopUp before Prototype)</li>
  <li>Cross-browser compatibility</li>
  <li>Fancy layouts, animations and transitions</li>
  <li>Auto-correction of size and position when required</li>
  <li>The possibility to create groups</li>
  <li>Support for AJAX requests</li>
  <li>And many more...</li>
</ul>

<h1 class="why_another_lightbox_like_library">Why another Lightbox-like Javascript library?</h1>
<p>
  Just like many among us, I had the need for a lightbox-like library to use for a website I was working on.
  After examining libraries such as <%= link_to "Lightbox2", "http://www.lokeshdhakar.com/projects/lightbox2/" %>, <%= link_to "LightWindow", "http://stickmanlabs.com/lightwindow/" %>, 
  <%= link_to "Highslide", "http://highslide.com/" %>, <%= link_to "Thickbox", "http://jquery.com/demo/thickbox/" %>, <%= link_to "ModalBox", "http://www.wildbit.com/labs/modalbox/" %> and
  many more, I haven't found one that really suited my needs. Either the installation was to complicated, the look-and-feel wasn't pretty, the transitions were glitchy, their were conflicts 
  with other libraries or the possibilities were lacking.
  <br><br>
  Enter TopUp! The installation of TopUp consists of including only one file (<strong>no images or stylesheets!</strong>), the look-and-feel is Apple-like, the animations and transitions look
   fancy, you can still use Prototype and last but not least:
  because of the flexibility of TopUp, it is so easy to specify options.
</p>

